# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quart-async
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quart-async/async-await] In computer programming, the **async/await pattern** is a syntactic feature of many programming languages that allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:quart-async/async-await] The feature is found in C#, C++, Python, F#, Hack, Julia, Dart, Kotlin, Rust, Nim, JavaScript, and Swift.
[src:quart-async/async-await] F# added asynchronous workflows with await points in version 2.0 in 2007.
[src:quart-async/async-await] This influenced the async/await mechanism added to C#.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Haskell lead developer Simon Marlow created the async package in 2010.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Microsoft first released a version of C# with async/await in the Async CTP (2011).
[src:quart-async/async-await] It was later officially released in C# 5 (2012).
[src:quart-async/async-await] Python added support for async/await with version 3.5 in 2015 adding 2 new keywords, `async` and `await`.
[src:quart-async/async-await] TypeScript added support for async/await with version 1.7 in 2015.
[src:quart-async/async-await] JavaScript added support for async/await in 2017 as part of ECMAScript 2017 JavaScript edition.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Rust added support for async/await with version 1.39.0 in 2019 using the `async` keyword and the `.await` postfix operator, both introduced in the 2018 edition of the language.
[src:quart-async/async-await] C++ added support for async/await with version 20 in 2020 with 3 new keywords `co_return`, `co_await`, `co_yield`.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Swift added support for async/await with version 5.5 in 2021, adding 2 new keywords `async` and `await`.
[src:quart-async/async-await] This was released alongside a concrete implementation of the Actor model with the `actor` keyword which uses async/await to mediate access to each actor from outside.
[src:quart-async/async-await] A function using async/await can use as many `await` expressions as it wants, and each will be handled in the same way (though a promise will only be returned to the caller for the first await, while every other await will utilize internal callbacks).
[src:quart-async/async-await] A function can also hold a promise object directly and do other processing first (including starting other asynchronous tasks), delaying awaiting the promise until its result is needed.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Functions with promises also have promise aggregation methods that allow the program to await multiple promises at once or in some special pattern (such as C#'s `Task.WhenAll()`, which returns a valueless `Task` that resolves when all of the tasks in the arguments have resolved).
[src:quart-async/async-await] Many promise types also have additional features beyond what the async/await pattern normally uses, such as being able to set up more than one result callback or inspect the progress of an especially long-running task.
[src:quart-async/async-await] In the particular case of C#, and in many other languages with this language feature, the async/await pattern is not a core part of the language's runtime, but is instead implemented with lambdas or continuations at compile time.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Because of this, if an interface method needs to return a promise object, but itself does not require `await` in the body to wait on any asynchronous tasks, it does not need the `async` modifier either and can instead return a promise object directly.
[src:quart-async/async-await] For instance, a function might be able to provide a promise that immediately resolves to some result value (such as C#'s `Task.FromResult()`), or it may simply return another method's promise that happens to be the exact promise needed (such as when deferring to an overload).
[src:quart-async/async-await] One important caveat of this functionality, however, is that while the code resembles traditional blocking code, the code is actually non-blocking and potentially multithreaded, meaning that many intervening events may occur while waiting for the promise targeted by an `await` to resolve.
[src:quart-async/async-await] The C language does not support await/async.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Some coroutine libraries such as *s_task* simulate the keywords await/async with macros.
[src:quart-async/async-await] In C++, await (named `co_await` in C++ to emphasise its context in coroutines) has been officially merged into C++20.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Support for it, coroutines, and the keywords such as `co_await` are available in GCC and MSVC compilers while Clang has partial support.
[src:quart-async/async-await] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:quart-async/async-await] To call it, use `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:quart-async/async-await] It is worth noting that `std::promise` and `std::future`, although it would seem that they would be awaitable objects, implement none of the machinery required to be returned from coroutines and be awaited using `co_await`.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Programmers must implement a number of public member functions, such as `await_ready`, `await_suspend`, and `await_resume` on the return type in order for the type to be awaited on.
[src:quart-async/async-await] In 2012, C# added the async/await pattern in C# with version 5.0, which Microsoft refers to as the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP).
[src:quart-async/async-await] Async methods usually return either `void`, `Task`, `Task<T>`, `ValueTask` or `ValueTask<T>`.
[src:quart-async/async-await] User code can define custom types that async methods can return through custom *async method builders* but this is an advanced and rare scenario.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Async methods that return `void` are intended for event handlers; in most cases where a synchronous method would return `void`, returning `Task` instead is recommended, as it allows for more intuitive exception handling (note that `Task<void>` is invalid in C#).
[src:quart-async/async-await] Methods that make use of `await` must be declared with the `async` keyword.
[src:quart-async/async-await] In methods that have a return value of type `Task<T>`, methods declared with `async` must have a return statement of type assignable to `T` instead of `Task<T>`; the compiler wraps the value in the `Task<T>` generic.
[src:quart-async/async-await] It is also possible to `await` methods that have a return type of `Task` or `Task<T>` that are declared without `async`.
[src:quart-async/async-await] The following async method downloads data from a URL using `await`.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Because this method issues a task for each URI before requiring completion with the `await` keyword, the resources can load at the same time instead of waiting for the last resource to finish before starting to load the next.
[src:quart-async/async-await] In 2007, F# added asynchronous workflows with version 2.0.
[src:quart-async/async-await] The asynchronous workflows are implemented as CE (computation expressions).
[src:quart-async/async-await] They can be defined without specifying any special context (like `async` in C#).
[src:quart-async/async-await] F# asynchronous workflows append a bang (!) to keywords to start asynchronous tasks.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Java does not have `async` and `await` keywords in the language, however it can be emulated using the `java.util.concurrent` package, such as the class `CompletableFuture` (introduced in Java 8).
[src:quart-async/async-await] Asynchronous programming is later improved in Java 21 with the introduction of virtual threads and structured task scopes.
[src:quart-async/async-await] The await operator in JavaScript (and TypeScript) can only be used from inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
[src:quart-async/async-await] If the parameter is a promise, execution of the async function will resume when the promise is resolved (unless the promise is rejected, in which case an error will be thrown that can be handled with normal JavaScript exception handling).
[src:quart-async/async-await] If the parameter is not a promise, the parameter itself will be returned immediately.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Many libraries provide promise objects that can also be used with await, as long as they match the specification for native JavaScript promises.
[src:quart-async/async-await] However, promises from the jQuery library were not Promises/A+ compatible until jQuery 3.0.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Node.js version 8 includes a utility that enables using the standard library callback-based methods as promises.
[src:quart-async/async-await] The Future::AsyncAwait module was the subject of a Perl Foundation grant in September 2018.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Python 3.5 (2015) has added support for async/await as described in PEP 492 (written and implemented by Yury Selivanov).
[src:quart-async/async-await] On November 7, 2019, async/await was released on the stable version of Rust.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Async functions in Rust desugar to plain functions that return values that implement the Future trait.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Currently they are implemented with a finite-state machine.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Swift 5.5 (2021) added support for async/await as described in SE-0296.
[src:quart-async/async-await] The async/await pattern is especially attractive to language designers of languages that do not have or control their own runtime, as async/await can be implemented solely as a transformation to a state machine in the compiler.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Supporters claim that asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written with async/await that looks almost like traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:quart-async/async-await] In particular, it has been argued that await is the best way of writing asynchronous code in message-passing programs; in particular, being close to blocking code, readability and the minimal amount of boilerplate code were cited as await benefits.
[src:quart-async/async-await] Critics of async/await note that the pattern tends to cause surrounding code to be asynchronous too; and that its contagious nature splits languages' library ecosystems between synchronous and asynchronous libraries and APIs, an issue often referred to as "function coloring".
[src:quart-async/async-await] Alternatives to async/await that do not suffer from this issue are called "colorless".
[src:quart-async/async-await] Examples of colorless designs include Go's goroutines and Java's virtual threads.
[src:quart-async/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] The **Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface** (**ASGI**) is a calling convention for web servers to forward requests to asynchronous-capable Python frameworks, and applications.
[src:quart-async/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] It is built as a successor to the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI).
[src:quart-async/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] Where WSGI provided a standard for synchronous Python applications, ASGI provides one for both asynchronous and synchronous applications, with a WSGI backwards-compatibility implementation and multiple servers and application frameworks.
[src:quart-async/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] ASGI is also designed to be a superset of WSGI, and there's a defined way of translating between the two, allowing WSGI applications to be run inside ASGI servers through a translation wrapper (provided in the asgiref library).
[src:quart-async/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] A threadpool can be used to run the synchronous WSGI applications away from the async event loop.
[src:quart-async/latest] Quart is a Fast Python web microframework.
[src:quart-async/latest] With all of the above possible using asynchronous (asyncio) libraries/code or synchronous libraries/code.
[src:quart-async/latest] Quart is an asyncio reimplementation of the popular Flask microframework API.
[src:quart-async/latest] This means that if you understand Flask you understand Quart.
[src:quart-async/latest] See Flask evolution to learn more about how Quart builds on Flask.
[src:quart-async/latest] Like Flask Quart has an ecosystem of extensions for more specific needs.
[src:quart-async/latest] In addition a number of the Flask extensions work with Quart.
[src:quart-async/latest] If you come across an issue, or have a feature request please open an issue.If you want to contribute a fix or the feature-implementation please do (typo fixes welcome), by proposing a merge request.
[src:quart-async/latest] If you want to ask for help try on discord.
[src:quart-async/latest] If you can’t find documentation for what you are looking for here, remember that Quart is an implementation of the Flask API and hence the Flask documentation is a great source of help.
[src:quart-async/latest] Quart is also built on the Jinja template engine and the Werkzeug toolkit.
[src:quart-async/latest] The Flask documentation is so good that you may be better placed consulting it first then returning here to check how Quart differs.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:quart-async/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] The **Web Server Gateway Interface** (**WSGI**, pronounced *whiskey* or *WIZ-ghee*) is a simple calling convention for web servers to forward requests to web applications or frameworks written in the Python programming language.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] The current version of WSGI, version 1.0.1, is specified in Python Enhancement Proposal (PEP) 3333.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was originally specified as PEP-333 in 2003.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] PEP-3333, published in 2010, updates the specification for Python 3.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] In 2003, Python web frameworks were typically written against only CGI, FastCGI, mod_python, or some other custom API of a specific web server.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was thus created as an implementation-neutral interface between web servers and web applications or frameworks to promote common ground for portable web application development.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] Between the server and the application, there may be one or more *WSGI middleware components*, which implement both sides of the API, typically in Python code.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI does not specify how the Python interpreter should be started, nor how the application object should be loaded or configured, and different frameworks and webservers achieve this in different ways.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] A WSGI middleware component is a Python callable that is itself a WSGI application, but may handle requests by delegating to other WSGI applications.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] These applications can themselves be WSGI middleware components.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] A full example of a WSGI network server is outside the scope of this article.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] Below is a sketch of how one would call a WSGI application and retrieve its HTTP status line, response headers, and response body, as Python objects.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] Details of how to construct the `environ` dict have been omitted.
[src:quart-async/web-server-gateway-interface] Currently wrappers are available for FastCGI, CGI, SCGI, AJP (using flup), twisted.web, Apache (using mod_wsgi or mod_python), Nginx (using ngx_http_uwsgi_module), Nginx Unit (using the Python language module), and Microsoft IIS (using WFastCGI, isapi-wsgi, PyISAPIe, or an ASP gateway).
[src:quart-async/websocket] WebSocket is distinct from HTTP used to serve most webpages.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Although they are different, RFC 6455 states that WebSocket "is designed to work over HTTP ports 443 and 80 as well as to support HTTP proxies and intermediaries", making the WebSocket protocol compatible with HTTP.
[src:quart-async/websocket] To achieve compatibility, the WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The WebSocket protocol enables full-duplex interaction between a web browser (or other client application) and a web server with lower overhead than half-duplex alternatives such as HTTP polling, facilitating real-time data transfer from and to the server.
[src:quart-async/websocket] This is achieved by providing a standardized way for the server to send content to the client without being first requested by the client, and allowing messages to be exchanged while keeping the connection open.
[src:quart-async/websocket] In this way, a two-way ongoing conversation can take place between the client and the server.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The communications are usually done over TCP port number 443 (or 80 in the case of unsecured connections), which is beneficial for environments that block non-web Internet connections using a firewall.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Additionally, WebSocket enables streams of messages on top of TCP.
[src:quart-async/websocket] TCP alone deals with streams of bytes with no inherent concept of a message.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Similar two-way browser–server communications have been achieved in non-standardized ways using stopgap technologies such as Comet or Adobe Flash Player.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Most browsers support the protocol, including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The WebSocket protocol specification defines `ws` (WebSocket) and `wss` (WebSocket Secure) as two new uniform resource identifier (URI) schemes that are used for unencrypted and encrypted connections respectively.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Apart from the scheme name and fragment (i.e.
[src:quart-async/websocket] `#` is not supported), the rest of the URI components are defined to use URI generic syntax.
[src:quart-async/websocket] WebSocket was first referenced as TCPConnection in the HTML5 specification, as a placeholder for a TCP-based socket API.
[src:quart-async/websocket] In June 2008, a series of discussions were led by Michael Carter that resulted in the first version of the protocol known as WebSocket.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Before WebSocket, port 80 full-duplex communication was attainable using Comet channels; however, Comet implementation is nontrivial, and due to the TCP handshake and HTTP header overhead, it is inefficient for small messages.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The WebSocket protocol aims to solve these problems without compromising the security assumptions of the web.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The name "WebSocket" was coined by Ian Hickson and Michael Carter shortly thereafter through collaboration on the #whatwg IRC chat room, and subsequently authored for inclusion in the HTML5 specification by Ian Hickson.
[src:quart-async/websocket] In December 2009, Google Chrome 4 was the first browser to ship full support for the standard, with WebSocket enabled by default.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Development of the WebSocket protocol was subsequently moved from the W3C and WHATWG group to the IETF in February 2010, and authored for two revisions under Ian Hickson.
[src:quart-async/websocket] After the protocol was shipped and enabled by default in multiple browsers, the RFC 6455 was finalized under Ian Fette in December 2011.
[src:quart-async/websocket] RFC 7692 introduced compression extension to WebSocket using the DEFLATE algorithm on a per-message basis.
[src:quart-async/websocket] A web application (e.g. web browser) may use the `WebSocket` interface to maintain bidirectional communications with a WebSocket server.
[src:quart-async/websocket] **Frame-based message** exchange: data, ping and pong messages.
[src:quart-async/websocket] **Closing handshake**: close message (request then echoed in response).
[src:quart-async/websocket] The client sends an **HTTP request** (**method** **GET**, **version ≥ 1.1**) and the server returns an **HTTP response** with **status code 101** (*Switching Protocols*) on success.
[src:quart-async/websocket] HTTP and WebSocket clients can connect to a server using the same port because the opening handshake uses HTTP.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Sending additional HTTP headers (that are not in the table below) is allowed.
[src:quart-async/websocket] After the *Switching Protocols* HTTP response, the opening handshake is complete, the HTTP protocol stops being used, and communication switches to a binary frame-based protocol.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The following Python code generates a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The following Python code calculates `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` using `Sec-WebSocket-Key` from the example request above.
[src:quart-async/websocket] `Sec-WebSocket-Key` and `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` are intended to prevent a caching proxy from re-sending a previous WebSocket conversation, and does not provide any authentication, privacy, or integrity.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Though some servers accept a short `Sec-WebSocket-Key`, many modern servers will reject the request with error "invalid Sec-WebSocket-Key header".
[src:quart-async/websocket] After the opening handshake, the client and server can, at any time, send **data messages** (text or binary) and **control messages** (*Close*, *Ping*, *Pong*) to each other.
[src:quart-async/websocket] A message is composed of **one frame if unfragmented** or **at least two frames if fragmented**.
[src:quart-async/websocket] A **client must mask** all frames sent to the server.
[src:quart-async/websocket] A **server must not mask** any frames sent to the client.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Frame masking applies **XOR between the payload and the masking key**.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The following pseudocode describes the algorithm used to both mask and unmask a frame.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The `permessage-deflate` extension allows data messages to be compressed using the DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:quart-async/websocket] For example, during the opening handshake, the client and server may use the following header to enable the extension.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The `RSV1` field of the first frame of a data message must be set to indicate the payload data is compressed.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Note: `recv()` returns up to the amount of bytes requested.
[src:quart-async/websocket] For readability, the code ignores that, thus it may fail in non-ideal network conditions.
[src:quart-async/websocket] A secure version of the WebSocket protocol is implemented in Firefox 6, Safari 6, Google Chrome 14, Opera 12.10 and Internet Explorer 10.
[src:quart-async/websocket] A detailed protocol test suite report lists the conformance of those browsers to specific protocol aspects.
[src:quart-async/websocket] An older, less secure version of the protocol was implemented in Opera 11 and Safari 5, as well as the mobile version of Safari in iOS 4.2.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The BlackBerry Browser in OS7 implements WebSockets.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Because of vulnerabilities, it was disabled in Firefox 4 and 5, and Opera 11.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Using browser developer tools, developers can inspect the WebSocket handshake as well as the WebSocket frames.
[src:quart-async/websocket] ASP.NET Core have support for WebSockets using the `app.UseWebSockets();` middleware.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Unlike regular cross-domain HTTP requests, WebSocket requests are not restricted by the same-origin policy.
[src:quart-async/websocket] It is better to use tokens or similar protection mechanisms to authenticate the WebSocket connection when sensitive (private) data is being transferred over the WebSocket.
[src:quart-async/websocket] A live example of vulnerability was seen in 2020 in the form of Cable Haunt.
[src:quart-async/websocket] WebSocket protocol client implementations try to detect whether the user agent is configured to use a proxy when connecting to destination host and port, and if it is, uses HTTP CONNECT method to set up a persistent tunnel.
[src:quart-async/websocket] The WebSocket protocol is unaware of proxy servers and firewalls.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Some proxy servers are transparent and work fine with WebSocket; others will prevent WebSocket from working correctly, causing the connection to fail.
[src:quart-async/websocket] In some cases, additional proxy-server configuration may be required, and certain proxy servers may need to be upgraded to support WebSocket.
[src:quart-async/websocket] If unencrypted WebSocket traffic flows through an explicit or a transparent proxy server without WebSockets support, the connection will likely fail.
[src:quart-async/websocket] If an encrypted WebSocket connection is used, then the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) in the WebSocket Secure connection ensures that an `HTTP CONNECT` command is issued when the browser is configured to use an explicit proxy server.
[src:quart-async/websocket] This sets up a tunnel, which provides low-level end-to-end TCP communication through the HTTP proxy, between the WebSocket Secure client and the WebSocket server.
[src:quart-async/websocket] In the case of transparent proxy servers, the browser is unaware of the proxy server, so no `HTTP CONNECT` is sent.
[src:quart-async/websocket] However, since the wire traffic is encrypted, intermediate transparent proxy servers may simply allow the encrypted traffic through, so there is a much better chance that the WebSocket connection will succeed if WebSocket Secure is used.
[src:quart-async/websocket] Using encryption is not free of resource cost, but often provides the highest success rate, since it would be travelling through a secure tunnel.
[src:quart-async/websocket] A mid-2010 draft (version hixie-76) broke compatibility with reverse proxies and gateways by including eight bytes of key data after the headers, but not advertising that data in a `Content-Length: 8` header.
[src:quart-async/websocket] This data was not forwarded by all intermediates, which could lead to protocol failure.
[src:quart-async/websocket] More recent drafts (e.g., hybi-09) put the key data in a `Sec-WebSocket-Key` header, solving this problem.
